\(\renewcommand{\hat}[1]{\widehat{#1}}\)

01_circle_to_wave


  1. Question

    We began by defining the trigonometric ratios of right triangles. We saw it was beneficial to move to unit-circle definitions to allow for any angle (not just acute angles of right triangles). Now, we will see that when we plot trigonometric functions, we get waves (and other periodic functions).

    In Desmos, you can store a list of angles (in radians) with the following expression: T=[0.478, 0.684, 1.33, 1.906, 2.137, 3.403, 3.725, 4.481, 5.167, 5.538]

    \[T=[0.478, 0.684, 1.33, 1.906, 2.137, 3.403, 3.725, 4.481, 5.167, 5.538]\]

    From that list of angles, you can plot the corresponding points on the unit circle with the following expression: (cos(T),sin(T)). Find the corresponding graph.


    • Plot matches the given list of angles.

    Now, in Desmos, you can type (T,sin(T)) to get the points along the sine wave. Find the corresponding graph.


    • Plot matches the given list of angles.

    Lastly, in Desmos, you can type (T,cos(T)) to get the points along the cosine wave. Find the corresponding graph.




    Solution

    We are hoping to see how the unit-circle points correspond to the points on the waves. I think this animation does a great job of showing that the sine wave is created by plotting the \(y\) coordinate (of the unit circle) as a function of time, and the cosine wave is created by plotting the \(x\) coordinate as a function of time (and the angle grows linearly in time).

    Here’s another attempt to show the connection between the unit circle and the sine wave:
